natural problem:
A square and four circles, each with a radius of 5 inches, are arranged as shown. What is the area, in square inches, of the square? [asy]
unitsize(1mm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7pt));

draw((0,0)--(20,0)--(20,20)--(0,20)--cycle);
draw(Circle((5,5),5));
draw(Circle((15,5),5));
draw(Circle((5,15),5));
draw(Circle((15,15),5));
[/asy]

a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 A square and four circles, each with a radius of 5 inches, are arranged as shown. What is the area, in square inches, of the square? [asy]
unitsize(1mm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7pt));

draw((0,0)--(20,0)--(20,20)--(0,20)--cycle);
draw(Circle((5,5),5));
draw(Circle((15,5),5));
draw(Circle((5,15),5));
draw(Circle((15,15),5));
[/asy] The final Answer is 400
 ### Proof
 The side length of the square is equal to twice the diameter of one of the circles, so the area of the square is $(20\text{ in})(20\text{ in})=\boxed{400}$ square inches.
 *)

theorem
fixes r s :: real
assumes h0 : "r = 5"
and h1 : "\<forall> x. s x = x * x"
and h2 : "s (2 * r) = 400"
shows  "s (2 * r) = 400"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer

